A non-governmental organisation, Unubiko Foundation has supported the fight against COVID-19 with the provision of 12,000 bottles of hand sanitisers for communities in Abam, Arochukwu local government area of Abia State. The foundation also created awareness on the pandemic in the communities and churches through radio jingles in Igbo and English Language as well as mobilisation of health officials to enlighten the people on the precautions to prevent the spread of the virus. Twelve communities of Ozu Abam, Ameke Abam , Idima Abam , Ndi Oji Abam, Amuru Abam, Ndi Agwu Abam , Ndi Ebe Abam , Atan Abam , Ndi Okwara Abam , Ndi Okereke Abam, and Ndi Okorie Abam benefitted from the programme The founder, Mr James Chijioke Umeh, said that the organisation considered it necessary to sensitise the rural populace of Abam on the life-threatening coronavirus which broke out in China and is currently plaguing the world and the safety measures. In a statement he issued yesterday, Ume said: “We provided more than 12,000 bottles of hand sanitisers and also paid for jingles in radio stations in Igbo and English Language to pass the message about COVID-19 situation on ground to the people,’’ he said. Also, the programme director of the foundation, Dr Benjamin Isani, said that the sensitisation campaign came at the right time as the coronavirus pandemic had ravaged some parts of Nigeria. He said: “From the standpoint of a medical doctor, I know that the rural areas lack proper information about the virus and on enquires, I discovered that they are ignorant about it. “We explained in detail how coronavirus can be contracted and the need for them to practice social distancing, proper hygiene, washing of hands with soap at least 20 minutes intervals, the proper use of hand sanitizers and also the basic signs and symptoms of the virus,’’ he said.